      <h2>The core principle: positive reinforcement</h2>
      <p>Our Nordic breeds are intelligent, sometimes stubborn, always sensitive. Methods based on physical punishment or forced dominance produce anxious or aggressive dogs. The scientifically validated method — and the only one we recommend — is <strong>positive reinforcement</strong>: reward what you want to see repeated, ignore what you don't want to encourage.</p>
      <div class="tip-box"><strong>The golden rule:</strong> Your dog does something you like? Reward immediately (within 2 seconds). Your dog does something you don't want? Calmly interrupt, redirect, and reward the correct alternative behaviour.</div>

      <h2>First commands (8–16 weeks)</h2>
      <p>The socialisation window is between 3 and 16 weeks of age. After that, learning remains possible but requires more effort. Make the most of the first weeks to teach:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sit</strong> — the foundational command that structures your relationship. Show a treat above the head, say "Sit" the moment the bottom touches the floor, reward immediately.</li>
        <li><strong>Down</strong> — from "Sit", gently guide the treat toward the floor. 10 repetitions per session, 2–3 sessions per day.</li>
        <li><strong>Recall</strong> — the most important command of all. Start in a closed space, call the name + "Come", reward generously every time. Never recall to scold.</li>
        <li><strong>Drop it / Leave it</strong> — critical for Pomsky and Husky who pick up everything. Always offer a treat exchange — never snatch forcefully.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Breed-specific tips</h2>
      <h3>Pomsky</h3>
      <p>The Pomsky combines Husky intelligence (fast boredom) with Pomeranian stubbornness. It learns quickly but may unilaterally decide the lesson is over. Key: keep sessions short (5–8 minutes maximum), varied, and always end on a success.</p>
      <h3>Pomeranian</h3>
      <p>Watch out for "small dog syndrome" — the tendency to let things slide that you'd never accept from a large breed. A Pomeranian that growls over its food bowl is a behavioural issue, regardless of size. Tiny doesn't mean excused.</p>
      <h3>Siberian Husky</h3>
      <p>The Husky is not a submissive dog. It evolved working as a team, taking initiative. It will respect you as a partner, not an absolute master. Intense physical exercise before training sessions dramatically improves concentration.</p>

      <h2>Toilet training</h2>
      <p>Puppies cannot control their bladder before 12–16 weeks. Until then: take them out immediately after every meal, every nap, every play session. Reward consistently outdoors. Accident indoors: clean with an enzyme cleaner (not ammonia), no punishment — they genuinely don't understand retrospective scolding.</p>
      <p>Most puppies from Cimes Blanches are 90% toilet-trained within 3–4 weeks at home, provided the protocol is followed consistently.</p>
